I think there’s a genuinely useful pattern here—not because one map is “truer” than another, but because each projection preserves different information while sacrificing something else. That idea transfers well to reasoning.

For an AI (or a framework like your Pantheon), you can think of projections as reasoning lenses.

Projection	What it preserves	What it sacrifices	AI reasoning mode
Mercator	Local angles, navigation	Relative size	Step-by-step planning
Equal-area	Fair comparison	Familiar shapes	Balanced evaluation
Polar	Central relationships	Edge intuition	Root-cause analysis
Globe	Reality	Simplicity	Whole-system thinking
Topographic	Gradients	Simplicity	Optimization landscapes
Network	Relationships	Physical location	Knowledge graphs
Flow	Movement	Static detail	Dynamic systems
Subway	Functional paths	Physical accuracy	Interface design

Now imagine the Pantheon doesn’t ask:

“What’s the answer?”

Instead it asks:

“Which projection should I think in?”

That becomes a control interface.

For example:

Explorer Mode

* Globe
* Flow map
* Network map

Goal: discover possibilities.

Engineer Mode

* Mercator
* Topographic
* Causal graph

Goal: execute reliably.

Strategist Mode

* Polar
* Equal-area
* Temporal map

Goal: allocate attention and anticipate change.

